| Independent Human Interface Guidelines                             |
|   from the because-somebody-has-to dept.                           |
|   posted by kdawson on Tuesday May 15, @21:08 (OS X)               |
|   http://apple.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/16/0043245        |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader alerts us to the [0]IndieHIG Wiki, which is an
independent effort to pick up the ball that Apple has dropped on human
interface guidelines (can you spell [1]FTFF?). From the wiki: "The
IndieHIG project is an initiative created out of the necessity to
document the new look and feel aspects of the Mac OS X experience,
outside of the supervision of Apple itself. The project is not intended
to replace, but rather to supplement the somewhat dated Apple Human
Interface Guidelines (HIG). There are many instances of Apple using new
and experimental interface styles, spurring developers to emulate these
styles in their own applications. Unfortunately, because Apple provides
neither guidelines nor code for developers to work with, the
implementation of these interface styles and features by third parties
can be lopsided and directionless. The IndieHIG intends to change this by
providing a comprehensive set of guidelines governing the use and
appearance of new, undocumented interface elements so that their
implementation by third party developers adheres to the unwritten
standards that Apple has set."

Discuss this story at:
    http://apple.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/16/0043245

Links:
    0. http://indiehig.com/wiki/Main_Page
    1. http://arstechnica.com/reviews/os/macosx-10-4.ars/18


