+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Appeals Court Denies Safe Harbor for Roommates.com                 |
|   from the appeals-court-says-don't-be-a-dick dept.                |
|   posted by ScuttleMonkey on Wednesday May 16, @17:43 (The Courts) |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/16/203206           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Mariner writes "The Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals [0]denied
Roommates.com Safe Harbor status under the Communications Decency Act in
a lawsuit brought by the Fair Housing Councils of San Fernando Valley and
San Diego. Roommates.com was accused of helping landlords discriminate
against certain kinds of tenants due to a couple of questions on the
Roommates.com registration form: gender and sexual orientation. 'Though
it refused to rule on whether Roommates.com actually violated the Fair
Housing Act, the Court did find that it lost Section 230 immunity because
it required users to enter that information in order to proceed. As Judge
Alex Kozinski put it in his opinion, "if it is responsible, in whole or
in part, for creating or developing the information, it becomes a content
provider and is not entitled to CDA immunity."'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/16/203206

Links:
    0. http://arstechnica.com/news.ars/post/20070516-sexual-orientation-questions-keep-roommates-com-from-safe-harbor-berth.html


