| What is Your Favorite Way to Make Coffee?                          |
|   from the good-to-the-last-drop dept.                             |
|   posted by Cliff on Wednesday May 16, @18:25 (Biotech)            |
|   http://ask.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/16/2123222          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

markov_chain asks: "For a while I've been making coffee using home-ground
whole beans and [0]a standard drip maker. I settled on this method for
its simplicity and good taste, even after trying numerous other methods
(such as the French press, [1]gravity percolators, and pressure
percolators), each coupled with either pre-ground or whole beans. So far,
the fresh ground beans are the only factor that made a significant
difference in taste. However, when I recently spotted a [2]a site that
vaguely extols freshness, I began to wonder how much the freshness of the
beans themselves affects the quality. Normally I thought the whole beans
would retain the quality far longer, due to less surface area exposed to
air, but clearly there still must be a decline; worse yet, it is
difficult to gauge that decline since the sellers usually do not
advertise the age of the beans. I would now like to pose a few questions.
What is your preferred coffee-making method, and how does it compare to
other methods you've tried? What are your favorite beans?"

